DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedNumeric");

$digit00 = random(1,8,1);
$digit01 = random(0,9,1);
$decimal0 = -($digit00*10+$digit01);

$digit10 = random(1,9,1);
$digit11 = random(0,9,1);
$digit12 = random(1,9,1);
$decimal1 = $digit10+$digit11/10+$digit12/100;

$dif = $decimal0 + $decimal1;

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Subtract these two decimals without using a calculator.

    [`` [$decimal0] + [$decimal1] = ``] [___________]{$dif}

END_PGML

##############################################

$absDif = abs($dif);

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

When we add a negative number with a positive number, we need to find the difference of their absolute values. When doing decimal subtractions, make sure to line up the decimal points. For the integer [`[$decimal0]`], the decimal point is at the end of the number, like in [`[$decimal0].00`]

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   &\phantom{-}[$digit00][$digit01].00 \\
 &\underline{-\phantom{[$digit00]}[$digit10].[$digit11][$digit12]\phantom{ad}} \\
   &\phantom{-}[$absDif]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Next, since the absolute value of [`[$decimal0]`] is bigger than that of [`[$decimal1]`], the result is negative.

*Solution:* [` [$decimal0] + [$decimal1] = [$dif] `]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

